{% doc %}

  Product — Model Info
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Fit-reference card showing the model's name, height, and the sizes they're
  wearing on the product shoot. Helps shoppers gauge fit on a real body.
  Figma 29:19 — 48×48 avatar on the left + name (11px medium uppercase)
  + height + size (10px) stacked right, 12px/16px padding, rounded-6.

  Data model — split across two metafields:

    1. A "Model" metaobject (Settings → Custom data → Metaobjects → Model)
       holds the reusable person-level info: name, height, avatar. One
       record per model, reused across every product they were shot in.

    2. A per-product single-line text metafield `custom.model_size` holds
       the specific size the model wore of THIS product. Size sits at
       product level because it varies per garment (e.g. Shaho wears M
       in a tee, L in a chunky knit) — keeping it on the Model record
       would force one size across every product.

  Product then references the Model record via a single metaobject-reference
  metafield: `product.metafields.custom.model`.

  Card only renders when a Model is linked AND that Model has a `name`.
  Every other field (height, avatar, size) is optional.

  Merchant setup:
    1. Settings → Custom data → Metaobjects → Add "Model"
         - name    (single-line text)
         - height  (single-line text)
         - avatar  (file reference → image)
    2. Settings → Custom data → Products → add metafields:
         - `custom.model`        — metaobject reference → Model
         - `custom.model_size`   — single-line text (e.g. "Shirt: M, Pant: M/32")
    3. Content → Metaobjects → Model → create records (SHAHO, etc.)
    4. Per product: pick the linked model + fill in `model_size`.

  @param {object} product - Required.

  @example
    {% render 'product-model-info', product: product %}

{% enddoc %}

{%- comment -%}
  `.value` on `custom.model` unwraps the metafield drop to the underlying
  Model metaobject drop. From there each field is accessible by its key
  (`model.name`, `model.height`). For the image, `avatar` is a
  file-reference → image, so `.value` yields a media_image drop usable
  by `image_url` / `image_tag`.

  `model_size` resolution: prefer the per-product metafield
  (`custom.model_size`, single-line text) because size varies per
  product — fall back to a `size` field on the Model metaobject
  itself for merchants who kept the original metaobject schema with
  size baked in. `| default:` triggers on nil OR empty string so either
  omitted case resolves cleanly.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- liquid
  assign model = product.metafields.custom.model.value
  assign model_name = model.name
  assign model_height = model.height
  assign model_avatar = model.avatar.value
  assign model_size = product.metafields.custom.model_size.value | default: model.size
-%}

{% if model_name != blank %}
  {%- comment -%}
    Heading + card structure mirrors the sibling Match With snippet so
    when the two render side by side (see `product-detail-form.liquid`'s
    Match With + Model Info row), their headings line up on the same
    y-axis. Card chrome itself (image, bg-surface, rounded, padding) is
    owned by the shared `product-meta-card` primitive — only the body
    (name + height + size lines) is Model-specific.

    Card fills its `flex-1` parent wrapper (sized in
    `product-detail-form.liquid` to equal 3 variant-picker tiles wide);
    width math lives there, not here.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-2">
    <h3 class="text-label-tight text-fg">
      {{ 'products.model' | t }}
    </h3>
    {%- capture meta_card_body -%}
      <p class="text-[12px] font-medium uppercase truncate w-full">{{ model_name }}</p>
      {% if model_height != blank %}
        <p class="text-[12px] truncate w-full">{{ model_height }}</p>
      {% endif %}
      {% if model_size != blank %}
        <p class="text-[12px] truncate w-full">{{ model_size }}</p>
      {% endif %}
    {%- endcapture -%}
    {% render 'product-meta-card',
              image: model_avatar,
              alt: model_name,
              body: meta_card_body
    %}
  </div>
{% endif %}
